nodes.label: Effort to disconnect
nodes.description: Effort which needs to be applied in order to seperate two cpmponents in disassembly

nodes.label: Required force/energy
nodes.description: Force which needs to be applied in order to seperate two components

nodes.label:
Size/complexity of
required tool
nodes.description: Kind of tools which are necessary to seperate two components in disassembly (from bare hands to welding or a heavy hammer)

nodes.label: Required time
nodes.description: Time which is necessary for seperating two cpmponents in disassembly

nodes.label:
Grouping of components 
regarding their technology lifetime
nodes.description: Measures whether components require the same time for becoming obsolescent due to technology change (different innovation cycles lead to components which need to be exvahnged more often, etc. electronics in manufacturing equipment)

nodes.label:
Grouping of components 
regarding their technical lifetime
nodes.description: Measures whether components require the same time for becoming obsolescent due to technical reasons (e.g. fatigue, corrosion etc.)

nodes.label:
Difficulty to access for
dismantling
nodes.description: Measure for the effort of removing one component from each other (e.g. because many other components have to be removed before)

nodes.label:
Grouping of components 
regarding their value lifetime
nodes.description: Measures whether components require the same time for becoming obsolescent not necessarily due to technical reasons (e.g. because of changing perception of aesthetics in fashion etc.)

nodes.label: Assembly Difficulty
nodes.description: Measures the difficulty of assembling components together

nodes.label: Tool size/complexity
nodes.description: Measures the required tool for assembling two components (from assembly by hand to large assembly machines).

nodes.label: Contact complexity
nodes.description: Measure for the complexity of assembling two components (e.g. if it is constrained by several connection points)

nodes.label:
Information-type
interaction factor
nodes.description: Measures the degree of information excahnge between two components

nodes.label:
Material-type
interaction factor
nodes.description: Measures the exchange of materials between components

nodes.label:
Spatial-type
interaction factor
nodes.description: Measures whether components need to be allocated adjacent to each other (e.g. to enable a certain function)..

nodes.label:
Energy-type
interaction factor
nodes.description: Measures whether energy transfer is necessary between components

nodes.label:
Grouping of components 
regarding their lifetime
nodes.description: Measures the degree to which components require the same time for becoming obsolescent or not

nodes.label: Complexity of contact
nodes.description: Measures amount and type of physical contact between two components (e.g. point contact vs multi-face-contact)

nodes.label: Tightness of contact
nodes.description: Measure for the type of physical contact between two components (e.g. from loose coupling via fasteners to close connection via welding)

nodes.label:
Grouping per assembly
process
nodes.description: Increase efficiency of assembly by clustering together components with same principles of assembly

nodes.label: Emissions
nodes.description: Solid, liquid & gaseous emissions along the product lifecycle, utilization of renewable &  non-renewable resources.

nodes.label: Customer value
nodes.description: increase coherence of product properties to customer requirements

nodes.label: Life Cycle Costs
nodes.description: Life Cycle costs refer to all costs which occur during product-lifetime. They can be allocated to multiple stakeholders (e.g. producing company, consumer, recycling company etc.)

nodes.label: Mass Customization
nodes.description: Mass Customization refers to products which can be customized to users preferences without loosing advantages of mass production, e.g. cost reduction via economies of scale. Examples: Dell computers, car market etc.

nodes.label: Disassembility
nodes.description: Indicates the effort for disassembling a product which is determined by the amount and type of component-interfaces.

nodes.label: Sorting complexity
nodes.description: Describes the effort for sorting components with homogenous properties for post-processing in the End-of life phase

nodes.label:
Service time
of materials
nodes.description: Temporal extension of material-usage

nodes.label:
Service time
of product/parts
nodes.description: Temporal extension of product/part usage

nodes.label: Ease of design changes
nodes.description: If a component needs to be changed several other components might be affected. The ease of a design change therefore refers to the amount and complexity of subsequent changes.

nodes.label: Learning curve
nodes.description: Increase of experience with time & output leads to better prouct quality

nodes.label: Retirement costs
nodes.description: Costs which occur in the End-of life phase of the product for recycling, remanufacturing, incineration etc.

nodes.label: Maintenance costs
nodes.description: Costs which occur for routine-inspections or repair incidents during the use phase of the product.

nodes.label: Disassembly costs
nodes.description: Costs which can be directly allocated to disassembly (e.g. wages, tools)

nodes.label: Assembly costs
nodes.description: Costs which occur within product assembly (e.g. wages, machines etc.)

nodes.label: Delayed differenciation
nodes.description: Limits inventory cost by keeping stock of final products minimal. The idea is to keep a higher stock of components which can be used for several products and to finalize them when the actual demand is known. E.g. Benetton keeps white sweaters and dyes them when the season-colour demand is known.

nodes.label: Inventory costs
nodes.description: Costs which occur for holding inventory (e.g. opportunity costs, obsolescence, theft etc.)

nodes.label:
Increased equipment
intensity
nodes.description: increase utilization of equipment, e.g. mashines for enabling economies of scale

nodes.label: Ease of concurrent engineering
nodes.description: Parallelization of design-tasks (e.g. parallel design of different components)

nodes.label: Decrease Internal Variety
nodes.description: Internal variety describes the amount of parts which is necessary to realize the product configurations offered to the customer.

nodes.label: External Variety
nodes.description: External variety refers to the multitude of product configurations which can be offered to the customer.
